text: Ketosynthase III as a gateway to engineering the biosynthesis of antitumoral benastatin derivatives Zhongli Xu a, Mikko Metsä-Ketelä b, Christian Hertweck a,c,∗ a Department of Biomolecular Chemistry, Leibniz Institute for Natural Product Research and Infection Biology–Hans-Knoell-Institute (HKI), Beutenbergstr. 11a, 07745 Jena, Germany b Division of Molecular Structural Biology, Department of Medical Biochemistry and Biophysics, Karolinska Institutet, Tomtebodavägen 6, 4tr, S-171 77 Stockholm, Sweden c Friedrich-Schiller-University, Jena, Germany Article history: Received 17 July 2008 Received in revised form 8 October 2008 Accepted 21 October 2008 Keywords: Antitumor agents Biosynthesis Fatty acids Polyketides Streptomyces Many aromatic polyketides such as the tetracyclins or anthra- cyclins represent valuable bacterial secondary metabolites that have been developed into therapeutics (Hertweck et al., 2007; Metsä-Ketelä et al., 2007). In many cases their complex archi- tectures are not readily accessible by chemical synthesis. Thus semi-synthetic strategies and pathway engineering are viable and complementary approaches to yield polyketide derivatives with altered bioactivity proﬁles and pharmacologically relevant prop- erties (Mendez and Salas, 2003; Reeves, 2003; Rix et al., 2002). j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / j b i o t e c Benastatins are aromatic polyketides from Streptomyces spp. that efﬁciently inhibit glutathione-S- transferases and induce apoptosis. Their biosynthesis involves a type II polyketide synthase, and a ketoacyl synthase (KAS) III component (BenQ) similar to FabH that is crucial for providing and selecting the rare hexanoate PKS starter unit. The function of BenQ as a KAS III was experimentally proven by point mutation of the active site cysteine. In the mutant several novel short chain fatty acid derived penta- and hexacyclic benastatin derivatives with antiprolieferative activities are formed. Strategies for engineering benastatin biosynthesis were attempted. Synthetic starter units surrogates were not incorporated by block mutants, which suggests that the primer needs to be enzyme-bound. Thus, on the basis of KAS III crystal struc- tures the three-dimensional structure of BenQ was modeled and the predicted substrate-binding tunnel was altered by individual mutations of potential gatekeeping residues (H95A and M99A). However, no signiﬁcant changes in substrate speciﬁcity were observed, indicating that there are other or additional gatekeeping amino acid residues in BenQ or secondary factors including likely protein–protein interac- tions between BenQ and the PKS complex, and possible conformational changes in BenQ. Finally, a benQ null mutant was complemented with butyrate starter unit biosynthesis genes from the alnumycin biosyn- thesis gene cluster, which resulted in a great (10×) enhancement in the production of butyrate-primed hexacyclic benastatin derivatives. The successful generation of an alnumycin–benastatin FAS-PKS hybrid pathway highlights the potential of metabolic pathways, which may lead to novel potential therapeutics and increased yields of desired natural products. The biosynthesis of polyphenolic compounds generally involves the repeated condensation of malonyl-CoA units in analogy to fatty acid biosynthesis (Rawlings, 1999; Shen, 2000). In stark contrast to the latter, the growing poly-(cid:2)-keto chain is not or is only par- tially reduced, thus giving rise to highly reactive intermediates that undergo enzyme-mediated cyclocondensations. A ketosyn- thase heterodimer (KS(cid:3) and KS(cid:2), or chain length factor, CLF) is usually sufﬁcient for polyketide assembly and determine the chain length, which usually ranges between 16 and 20 carbons (Keatinge- Clay et al., 2004). Then, cyclases, ketoreductases and aromatases shape the overall structure of the polyphenolic ring systems before ﬁnal tailoring reaction like alkylation, oxygenation and glycosyla- tion take place (Rix et al., 2002). Surprisingly, the vast majority of polyketides is solely derived from malonyl-derived acetate building blocks and features predominantly tri- or tetracyclic linear or angu- lar core structures. Pathways involving alternative acyl starter units (Moore and Hertweck, 2002) or extended ring topologies (Jakobi and Hertweck, 2004; Lackner et al., 2007) are rather exceptional. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. Many impressive examples have demonstrated that the eluci- dation of novel biochemical principles of polyketide biosynthesis sets the basis for rationally engineering biosynthetic pathways. To this end, the small family of benastatins (1–4, Fig. 1) pro- duced by Streptomyces spp. appeared to be an attractive target for biosynthetic studies. The ‘pentangular’ phenolic compounds have attracted considerable interest as potent glutathione-S-transferase (GST) inhibitors and inducers of apoptosis (Aoyagi et al., 1992; Aoyama et al., 1992b; Kakizaki et al., 2000). From a structural point of view, the benastatins stand out because of their unusual bent pentacyclic ring system and the pentyl side chain that is derived from a hexanoyl starter unit (Aoyama et al., 1992a). To elucidate and engineer the biosynthetic pathway we have recently cloned and sequenced the entire gene locus coding for benastatin biosyn- thesis (Fig. 1) (Xu et al., 2007). The identity of the biosynthetic Fig. 2. Priming of the ben PKS by linear and branched short chain fatty acids results in the formation of tetra- and pentacyclic polyphenols (R CH3 or OH). Z. Xu et al. / Journal of Biotechnology 140 (2009) 107–113

gene cluster was ﬁrmly established by its successful expression in the heterologous hosts Streptomyces lividans and Streptomyces albus (Xu et al., 2007). By excision of nonessential ﬂanking regions the essential coding region was narrowed down to ∼17 kb. Based on homology searches and frame analyses we identiﬁed 14 prob- able structural genes and three regulatory and resistance genes in the benastatin (ben) biosynthesis gene cluster. We have shown by heterologous expression of complete and incomplete sets of benas- tatin biosynthesis genes and the characterization of the metabolites produced that the unusual geminal bis-methylation is catalyzed by a single C-methyltransferase, BenF (Schenk et al., 2007), and that BenL is required for regioselective C-19 ketoreduction (Lackner et al., 2007). Furthermore, we found that BenQ, a FabH-like ketoacyl- synthase (KAS III) component, plays a crucial role in providing and selecting the rare hexanoate PKS starter unit. In the absence of BenQ alternative branched and straight-chain acyl starter units from the fatty acid biosynthesis pool are employed, yielding several novel penta- and hexacyclic benastatin derivatives (6–9, Fig. 2) (Xu et al., 2007). If the shorter straight-chain butyrate starter unit is utilized, unexpectedly, the length of the polyketide backbone is increased, resulting in the formation of an extended, hexacyclic ring system (6–9). The product levels of these new compounds were signiﬁ- cantly lower compared to the wild type (30%), however, some of these compounds showed different bioactivity proﬁles, i.e. com- parable antiproliferative effects but lower cytotoxicity. Here we report our approaches to alter the metabolic proﬁle of benastatin producers by mutating and exchanging the KAS III. 2.1. Cloning and heterologous expression of benQ in Escherichia coli

Construction of the C4 starter unit gene cassette that was co-expressed with BenQ* (KSIII mutant) in S. albus

Alnumycin biosynthetic genes required for starter unit synthesis reside scattered in the gene cluster (Oja et al., 2008). Therefore, indi- vidual genes were ﬁrst PCR-ampliﬁed together with their RBS signal sequences (underlined in forward primers) using primer pairs alnI- for: 5(cid:4)-TCT AGA GCA GCC GAT ACG GAG GAG AGG G-3(cid:4) and alnIrev: 5(cid:4)-AGC GCT TCA CGG CAG AAC CAC CAC CTG G-3(cid:4), alnKfor: 5(cid:4)-AGC GCT GGC GAG GGA GGT CCC GTG GAG C-3(cid:4) and alnKrev: 5(cid:4)-AGG CCT GTC CAA GGT CAG CTC ACC ACT G-3(cid:4), alnJfor: 5(cid:4)-AGG CCT TCG AGT GCG ACC GCA CAG GGT G-3(cid:4) and alnJrev: 5(cid:4)-TTA ATT AAG GGA TCA CAC AGT GGT GAG CTG-3(cid:4), cloned by using the TOPO-TA Cloning Kit (Invitrogen, USA) and sequenced. Subsequently, the genes were constructed into an artiﬁcial operon structure alnL (KSIII), alnK (AT) and alnJ (ACP) by using unique restriction sites generated in the PCR ampliﬁcation step. The restriction sites at both ends as well as in-between the genes are in the order XbaI (upstream of alnL), Eco47III, Eco147I and HindIII (downstream of alnJ). The ermEp pro- moter was cloned from plasmid pIJE486 (Ylihonko et al., 1996) as a Klenow-treated EcoRI–HindIII fragment to the integrating vector pSET152 (Bierman et al., 1992), which was cut with EcoRI and blunt ended, to generate plasmid pESET152. The alnumycin biosynthetic genes were cloned as a Klenow-treated XbaI–

indIII fragment to the integrating vector pSET152 (Bierman et al., 1992), which was cut with EcoRI and blunt ended, to generate plasmid pESET152. The alnumycin biosynthetic genes were cloned as a Klenow-treated XbaI–HindIII fragment to the EcoRV site of pESET152 to give the ﬁnal expression construct pMMK2. Finally, the expression construct was passed through E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 and conjugated to S. albus.

2.7. Fermentation and metabolic proﬁling Fermentation, extraction, and HPLC monitoring were conducted as described previously (Lackner et al., 2007; Schenk et al., 2007; Xu et al., 2007). Relative production rates were estimated by inte- gration of peaks. The metabolic proﬁle of a strain heterologously expressing the benastatin biosynthesis genes except for benQ is dramatically altered in contrast to the wild type. While natural benastatins are obviously derived from hexanoate, all polyketides produced by the mutant have incorporated alternate starter units from the fatty acid biosynthesis pool (Fig. 2) (Xu et al., 2007). The aim of this study was to demonstrate the essential role of BenQ as a KAS III in PKS prim- ing and to explore ways to alter the proﬁle of benastatin derivatives with KAS III variants. BenQ is related to various enzymes belonging to the KAS III (FabH) family (Tsay et al., 1992), such as ZhuH from the R1128 pathway (Marti et al., 2000) and AlnI from the recently identiﬁed alnumycin pathway (Oja et al., 2008). Common to all functional KAS III is a catalytic triad composed of Cys112, His244, and pXU317(BenQ H95A), pXU323(BenQ M99A) Asn274 (ecFabH numbering) in the active centre that performs the transacylation, decarboxylation and condensation reactions (Davies et al., 2000). It appeared likely that the gene product of benQ is a KAS III involved in both synthesizing the hexanoyl starter unit in analogy to fatty acid biosynthesis and loading the primer onto the PKS.

First, we sought to experimentally conﬁrm the proposed cat- alytic role of the BenQ ketosynthase function. For this purpose we mutated the critical Cys124 in the active site of BenQ to serine. The mutated benQ (C124S) was obtained by site-directed muta- genesis and was cloned into E. coli–Streptomyces shuttle vector pEM4a, yielding plasmid pXU329. This plasmid as well as a vec- tor harboring the ben biosynthesis genes except for benQ (pXU132) were introduced into S. albus. The transconjugant was grown in liquid media and its metabolic proﬁle was monitored by HPLC- MS. As expected, the biosynthesis of hexanoate-derived benastatins was fully impaired in the BenQ (C124S) mutant, clearly proving the essential role of the active site Cys124 in starter unit biosyn- thesis. Instead of the hexanoate-derived benastatin derivatives, the characteristic (cid:2)benQ mutant metabolites 5–9 were produced. We next attempted to chemically complement the lacking starter unit by pulse-feeding hexanoic acid and the corresponding N- acetylcysteamine thioester. However, these supplementations did not result in an alteration of the metabolic proﬁle. This observation is in agreement with our observation that various synthetic N-acyl cysteine thioester surrogates are not accepted by the ben type II PKS (Schenk, Xu, Hertweck, unpublished results) and strongly suggests that the priming unit needs to be bound to an enzyme or an acyl carrier protein before it is loaded onto the PKS. The ﬁnding that rigorously no alternative primers are loaded onto the PKS in the presence of a functional BenQ indicates that the KAS III functions as a gatekeeper. To get an insight into the molecular ground of PKS primer selection we next aimed at mutating and exchanging BenQ.

The high sequence similarity between BenQ and related KAS III enzymes, for which protein structures have been experimen- tally determined such as ZhuH, allowed us to build a model of BenQ by SWISS-MODEL (Guex and Peitsch, 1997; Schwede et al., 2003). Two major loops (L3 and L9) at the interface of the KAS III dimer are supposed to be critical for substrate recognition. In the case of ZhuH Met90 (on L3) and Thr96(cid:4) (on L3(cid:4)) determine the size of the substrate-binding pocket (Fig. 3). Accordingly, ZhuH can accomodate an acyl chain of up to four carbons, with up to one branch or substitutent on the carbon chain (Pan et al., 2002). In Fig. 3. Xu et al. / Journal of Biotechnology 140 (2009) 107–113 Table 1 Comparison of amino acid sequences deﬁning loop 3 (L3). fact, ZhuH is not only preferentially primed by isobutyryl or propi- onyl groups but also tolerates acetyl and butyryl, but not isovaleryl, primer units (Marti et al., 2000; Meadows and Khosla, 2001). The T96 amino acid is generally well conserved, but there is more varia- tion at the position of the M90 residue. Variations at these residues can especially be seen when compared against BenQ and mtFabH from Mycobacterium tuberculosis that catalyzes the formation of long non-branched fatty acids involved in cell wall biosynthesis (Musayev et al., 2005) (Table 1).

As for BenQ, the model suggested that the residues of His86 and Met90(cid:4) might protrude into the proposed L3–L3(cid:4) acyl binding pocket account for the substrate speciﬁcity. Because of the bulky side chains this priming ketosynthase does not tolerate branched acyl substrates and prefers the short straight-chain C4 building block. To test this hypothesis we enlarged the substrate-binding tunnel by individual H95A and M99A mutations. Then, we con- structed a double mutant in which both sites we changed into alanine. The resulting benQ variants were cloned into pEM4a, yielding plasmids pXU317(BenQ H95A), pXU323(BenQ M99A) and pXU327(BenQ H95AM99A), respectively, and individually intro- duced into S. albus/pXU132 by intergenic conjugation using E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 as the donor host. Co-expression of benQ vari- ants with the incomplete ben gene cluster resulted in a decreased production of benastatins; however, no novel benastatin deriva- tives were detectable. Furthermore, despite the enlarged active site cavity the titers of alternative branched chain acyl starters were not raised. Apparently, in the case of BenQ, enlarging the enzyme cavity is not sufﬁcient for altering PKS priming, and we turned towards the exchange of the entire KAS III component. A possible approach to yield predominantly butyrate-derived hexacyclic benastatin derivatives would be increasing the supply of the non-natural building block by generating a hybrid pathway. 2008). In all cases the biosynthetic pathways involves additional KAS III, an AT, and ACP for loading the non-acetate starter onto the PKS (Moore and Hertweck, 2002). Interestingly, despite high sequence similarity these modules exhibit some substrate ﬂexi- bility. Khosla and coworkers have shown that zhu PKS is primed with butyryl, valeryl or 4-methylvaleryl starter units, yielding var- ious alkyl-substituted anthraquinones (Marti et al., 2000; Tang et al., 2004b). The frenolicin PKS, on the other hand, may be primed with acetate and butyrate, respectively (Bibb et al., 1994; Moore and Hertweck, 2002). The pathway leading to the alnumycin appears to be the most stringent since only butyrate-primed metabolites have been isolated from producing strains (Bieber et al., 1998; Naruse et al., 1998). Analysis of the biosynthetic gene cluster and homol- ogy searches suggested that the butyryl starter of alnumycin is likely synthesized by the putative KAS III AlnI with participation of acyltransferase AlnJ, and a cognate acyl carrier protein AlnK (Oja et al., 2008). To cross-complement the (cid:2)benQ mutant we constructed a cassette of alnIJK genes by using unique restriction sites generated in the PCR-ampliﬁcation step. The aln genes were then cloned downstream of the ermEp promoter of pESET152, a derivative of integrating vector pSET152, to yield ﬁnal expression construct pMMK2. Both the cosmid harboring the ben gene clus- ter except for benQ and pMMK2 were introduced into S. albus by conjugation. Analysis of the HPLC proﬁle of the extract from the fer- mentation broth showed that the co-expression resulted in a great enhancement (10×) in the production of the four butyrate-derived benastatin derivatives benastatin F–I (Fig. 4).

The deduced gene product of benQ is a (cid:2)-ketoacyl-ACP synthase III (KAS III), a homolog of FabH. This component of the type II fatty acid synthase system in E. coli was ﬁrst identiﬁed by Jackowski and Rock (1987). FabH catalyzes the condensation of acetyl-CoA with malonyl-ACP to initiate the cycles of fatty acid elongation. Its position at the beginning of the pathway indicates its impor- tance in determining the fatty acid structure to be straight- or branched-chain, an even- or odd-numbered (Rock and Jackowski, 2002). In a polyketide biosynthetic gene cluster, the presence of such an additional ketosynthase usually indicates the synthesis of Z. Xu et al. / Journal of Biotechnology 140 (2009) 107–113

a non-acetate primed product (Hertweck et al., 2007; Moore and Hertweck, 2002). For example, the KAS III homolog DpsC is involved in propionate priming of the daunorubicin polyketide synthase (Bao et al., 1999). FrnI is able to initiate frenolicin biosynthesis with a butyryl-starter (Bibb et al., 1994), and R1128 A–D biosynthesis begins with various short-chain fatty acyl starter units under the control of substrate-relaxed ZhuH (Marti et al., 2000). Inactivation and (cross) complementation experiments have shown that these KAS III homologs are involved in the synthesis or activation of spe- ciﬁc primers and their subsequent transfer to the corresponding PKS (Florova et al., 2002; Han et al., 1998; Li et al., 2005; Metsä- Ketelä et al., 2003; Smirnova and Reynolds, 2001; Tang et al., 2004a). Our functional studies revealed the crucial role of BenQ role in benastatin biosynthesis. In the benQ knockout mutant, both straight-chain butyryl-CoA and branched-chain isohexanoyl-CoA are accepted by the elongation enzymes, whereas the regular pentyl-substituted benastatins are exclusively detectable in strains equipped with BenQ. Both the amino acid sequence homology as well as the identiﬁcation of the essential active site cysteine indicated that BenQ is a new member of the FabH family. BenQ shares highest sequence similarity (47% identity/66% similarity) with the R1128 PKS priming ketosynthase ZhuH. The crystal structure of ZhuH has been solved by Pan et al, which set the basis for identiﬁcation of factors governing PKS starter unit speciﬁcity (Pan et al., 2002). To get a ﬁrst insight into the substrate speciﬁcity of BenQ we have modeled its three-dimensional structure by align- ment with published FabH crystal structures. (Pan et al., 2002). To get a ﬁrst insight into the substrate speciﬁcity of BenQ we have modeled its three-dimensional structure by align- ment with published FabH crystal structures. (cid:2)-Ketosynthases like ZhuH function as homodimer, and the interactions between two major loops (L3 and L9) in the interface of the dimer structure are supposed to be important for substrate recognition (Pan et al., 2002). Modeling studies suggested that the acyl group-binding pocket, stretching from Cys121 in the catalytic center to the L3–L3(cid:4) architecture is important for deﬁning the substrate speciﬁcity of ZhuH. The acyl group-binding pocket of ZhuH is lined by hydropho- bic residues whose ﬂoor is formed by Met90 on L3 and Thr96e on L3(cid:4), the side chains of which also determined the size of the acyl group-binding pocket (Pan et al., 2002). With respect to BenQ, the presence of His86 on one monomer, which according to the model protruded its voluminous side chain into the L3–L3(cid:4) architecture, and the bulky aliphatic residue Met90(cid:4) on the other monomer, which also point into the acyl group-binding pocket (Fig. 3), might account for the different substrate speciﬁcities of BenQ and ZhuH. As a result, this priming ketosynthase would unlikely tolerate branched acyl-CoA, but straight-chain substrates consisting of up to four carbon atoms. Moreover, considering the fatty acyl supply in Streptomyces spp. and the comparatively rigid primer-binding domain of BenQ, butyryl-CoA might be the most promising (or only) candidate available in the cell. However, replacing the tar- geted amino acids with alanine have only resulted in a decreased production of the typical hexanoate-derived benastatins. Fur- thermore, the hampered feeding experiments suggested that an intimate interaction between the FabH component and the PKS seems to be indispensable for polyketide biosynthesis. Apparently, there are other or additional gatekeeping amino acid residues in BenQ or secondary factors including likely protein–

Apparently, there are other or additional gatekeeping amino acid residues in BenQ or secondary factors including likely protein–protein interactions between BenQ and the PKS complex, and possible conformational changes in BenQ, which have recently been sug- gested to occur in mtFabH (Sachdeva et al., 2008), that affect starter unit substrate speciﬁcity. We thus decided to exchange the entire FabH component to engineer the benastatin pathway.

To complement the (cid:2)benQ mutant and to channel the path- way towards the unusual buryrate-derived hexacyclic benastatins we constructed a gene cassette required for priming the alnumycin PKS with a butyryl starter unit (Fig. 5). Co-expression of the aln genes resulted in a great (10×) enhancement in the production of Fig. 5. Models for alnumycin biosynthesis involving the priming cassette AlnIJK for butyryl-ACP formation and engineered a benastatin-alnumycin hybrid pathway by KAS III loading domain swapping. butyrate-primed benastatin derivatives. This clear result suggests that AlnI is far more effective than the endogenous FAS FabH in com- plementing the BenQ mutant. Furthermore, the result also gives strong experimental evidence for the preferred substrate speci- ﬁcity of AlnI towards non-branched substrates as the pathway was directed towards the hexacyclic polyphenols. Although the pos- sibility of a 3-oxo-hexanoyl-ACP primer cannot be excluded on the basis of the in vivo experiments, the utilization of a butyrate starter as in the alnumycin pathway is the more likely scenario. In this context, it is also interesting to note, given the differences in substrate speciﬁcity, that the L3 region of AlnI is almost identi- cal in sequence to that of ZhuH (Table 1). Our results indicate that the physical association between the starter-unit setup and PKS is indispensable for efﬁcient and proper initiation of non-acetate primed polyketides biosynthesis. They clearly identiﬁed BenQ as a FabH-like KAS III that functions as a gateway to engineering the biosynthesis of antitumoral benastatin derivatives. The success- ful alnumycin–benastatin gene complementation underlines the potential of creating FAS-PKS hybrid pathways for manipulating the biosynthesis and increasing yields of desired natural products.
